      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must be under version control with documented regression test suite covering turbulence and scalar-transport modules relevant to hemolysis prediction.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is employed under a validated quality management system. Version control, regression testing covering turbulent flow and species transport, and documented release notes are all confirmed. SQA level meets MRL-5 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) or equivalent order-of-accuracy test must confirm spatial and temporal discretisation schemes for Navier-Stokes and hemolysis scalar transport.",
      "rationale": "MMS studies confirm second-order spatial accuracy for velocity and pressure fields. Temporal accuracy verified with a manufactured transient solution. Hemolysis scalar transport convergence confirmed via Richardson extrapolation. Code verification requirements satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be reported for hemolysis index QoI across at least three systematically refined meshes; GCI must be below 5% on the fine grid.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined meshes (4.2 M, 12.1 M, 31.8 M cells) were evaluated. GCI for hemolysis index on the fine grid is 3.1%, satisfying the sub-5% threshold. Spatial discretisation error is adequately characterised and below the required tolerance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must match COU operating envelope (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity) within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro experiments used bovine blood at 37 °C with viscosity matched to within 4% of clinical VAD operating conditions. Flow rates span 3–6 L/min and rotational speeds 2000–3000 RPM, fully covering the COU envelope. Test condition fidelity is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., validation metric u_val or ASME V&V 20 area metric) must be computed for hemolysis index across all validation operating points, with experimental uncertainty bands reported.",
      "rationale": "ASME V&V 20 area validation metric computed at all five operating points. Experimental hemolysis index uncertainty (95% CI) propagated through repeat measurements (n=8 per condition). Model predictions fall within experimental uncertainty bands at 4 of 5 conditions; the fifth shows a 7% overprediction within the expanded uncertainty envelope. Quantitative comparison satisfies Level 4 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (hemolysis index) must be the same metric used in the regulatory submission and must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint.",
      "rationale": "The normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) is the primary QoI in both the validation study and the regulatory submission. NIH is directly linked to plasma-free haemoglobin thresholds used in clinical evaluation. QoI relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on a geometry representative of the FDA generic centrifugal pump and at operating conditions within the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were performed on the FDA benchmark centrifugal pump geometry. Operating conditions in the validation campaign are a strict subset of the COU envelope. Validation activities are directly relevant to the intended COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated for all residuals to below 1e-5; round-off error sensitivity must be assessed.",
      "rationale": "All continuity, momentum, and scalar transport residuals converged to below 1e-6. Double-precision arithmetic employed throughout. Round-off error assessed via single/double precision comparison; difference in NIH prediction is less than 0.01%. Solver error requirements are met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be independently reviewed by a qualified analyst not involved in model development; boundary condition and material property inputs must be traceable to source data.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior CFD engineer reviewed all boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings against the documented simulation plan. All inputs are traceable to the experimental dataset and manufacturer fluid specifications. No use errors identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis model form (power-law scalar damage model) must be validated against an independent dataset not used in parameter calibration, demonstrating predictive accuracy within 15% of measured NIH across the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "The power-law hemolysis damage model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger formulation with Morrison coefficients) has been extensively applied in the cardiovascular CFD literature and is recognised as the de facto standard for centrifugal pump hemolysis prediction. Calibration was performed against a large prior dataset (n=42 operating conditions across three pump geometries), providing substantial empirical grounding for the model coefficients. Expert panel review involving five independent biofluid mechanics specialists confirmed that the model form captures the dominant shear-exposure damage mechanism relevant to VAD operating conditions. Although a fully independent hold-out validation dataset was not assembled for this specific submission — the available experimental data were used in coefficient refinement — the breadth of the prior calibration corpus and the consistency of predictions across geometrically distinct pumps provide strong indirect evidence of model form adequacy. Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis further demonstrates that NIH predictions are relatively insensitive to ±10% perturbations in model coefficients, suggesting that residual coefficient uncertainty does not materially affect the regulatory conclusion. On this basis, and given the absence of a superior validated alternative model form for this QoI at MRL 5, the assessment team judges the model form credibility to be sufficient for the intended COU, notwithstanding the formal gap relative to the independent-dataset criterion."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All uncertain model inputs (fluid viscosity, blood density, pump geometry tolerances) must be characterised with probability distributions and propagated through Monte Carlo UQ to produce a distribution of NIH predictions.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ performed with 5000 Latin hypercube samples across six uncertain inputs: dynamic viscosity (log-normal, CV=8%), blood density (normal, CV=1%), pump clearance gap (uniform ±50 µm), inlet velocity profile shape parameter (uniform ±15%), hemolysis model coefficient C (log-normal, CV=12%), and hemolysis model exponent α (normal, CV=6%). Full propagation yields 95th-percentile NIH prediction below clinical threshold. Input characterisation meets Level 4 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples must be characterised for haematocrit, plasma-free haemoglobin baseline, and storage age; inter-sample variability must be reported.",
      "rationale": "All blood samples characterised at haematocrit 35±2%, baseline plasma-free haemoglobin below 20 mg/dL, and storage age under 48 hours. Inter-sample variability in NIH reported as CV=9.3% across the 8-replicate measurement series. Sample characterisation satisfies Level 3 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameters used in the computational model must be demonstrated to be equivalent to those measured or controlled in the validation experiment within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, outlet pressure) replicated from experimental control logs with less than 2% deviation. Fluid properties mapped from experimental characterisation data. Geometric model derived from CMM measurement of the physical test article with surface deviation below 25 µm. Parameter equivalency is confirmed across all inputs."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following comprehensive review of all 13 credibility factors at Model Risk Level 5, the assessment team concludes that the simulation package provides sufficient credibility to support regulatory use of the CFD hemolysis prediction for the Class III VAD device. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility levels, including the critical quantitative output comparison (Level 4) and model inputs uncertainty quantification (Level 4). The single factor with a formal level shortfall — Model Form (achievedLevel 2 vs. requiredLevel 3) — was reviewed in depth by the team. The indirect evidence base for the power-law damage model is substantial: the model has been calibrated against 42 operating conditions across multiple pump geometries, has received expert panel endorsement, and Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis demonstrates low sensitivity of regulatory conclusions to residual coefficient uncertainty. The team judges that this indirect evidence, while not formally satisfying the independent-dataset criterion, is sufficient in the context of the overall evidence package and the absence of a validated alternative model. All other verification, validation, and uncertainty quantification activities are complete and meet MRL-5 requirements. The overall credibility evidence is judged adequate to support the intended regulatory decision.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
